reply_text:
@darkestlight6784 So you going to let someone attack and bully your child? Only people with kids understand. If you want respect from anyone you also need to be respectful to others(which that lady was not). I don’t care who are!

None of the children did nothing wrong but play outside with each other. They were not in her space so how is that a problem? That lady was definitely a weirdo who don’t need neighbors at all. 

That’s like someone telling a neighbor they can’t have company at their house just because you don’t like looking at people outside. Like you have no right because it’s not your property….now if you don’t like neighbors you should move…simple as that!!

@GFY94

I mean, why did the children need that little green patch of grass? There was so much space to play you can’t rollerskate on grass, and there are plenty of other places to play football. When the police officer said, “I’d rather you be outside playing than on TikTok,” it honestly annoyed me. I felt the officers should have maintained a more neutral stance instead of personalising the situation based on what they themselves might have enjoyed as children. Just being a child doesn’t give anyone the right to cause havoc in someone else’s home or neighbourhood.

I also feel like children lie sometimes, and it seemed the officers were taking their word as absolute truth. I think Susan could’ve benefited from having CCTV, and honestly, so could the other parents. Relying on actual evidence rather than opinions and feelings might have prevented a lot of misunderstandings and conflicts.

@posttoastieswithhoney My thoughts exactly after watching the documentary. For me, this wasn’t a profound or emotionally moving film it highlighted terrible policing and really made me think about the state of the world we live in.

I mean, look at Susan a single woman who worked and contributed positively to society. Let’s take what she did out of the equation for a moment. Now look at the parents who were interviewed, excluding AJ, of course. Who were they, and what were they like? One woman had a visible drug and alcohol problem and was even missing teeth.

What’s even more striking is that the documentary completely bypassed the children tormenting her, the adult parents enabling that behaviour, and the police officers who treated it like a joke and clearly also tormented her. All of this was caught on camera, yet it barely gets acknowledged.

@sweet_amir I just finished watching the documentary and hold a dissenting opinion regarding Susan Lorincz. I absolutely don’t condone what she did — she will have to live with the consequences for the rest of her life.

That said, the neighbourhood looked awful. The parents seemed rough, and one lady was clearly high and even drinking a beer at night. I can only imagine what it was like for her: dealing with the children during the day, whose behaviour was enabled by their parents, and then having to face the parents themselves in the evening. It really felt like a pack mentality, with everyone feeding off each other’s opinions and actions.

This situation could’ve been avoided. The kids could have found somewhere else to play they didn’t need that little green patch to be happy.

@AK-ng7lc

Yes, all the drug-addicted, benefits-seeking parents who were friendly with one another and ganged up on a woman who did not partake in their lifestyle were completely in the wrong. The unfortunate thing was that she moved to an area where everybody shared the same mentality, so she immediately stuck out like a sore thumb.

This whole idea of “road ownership” is crazy. Just because they had lived there slightly longer than she did doesn’t give them the right to bully, harass, or intimidate a woman who was simply trying to make a living. She was probably fed up with working from home and having to listen to the chaos outside. The kids should have played somewhere else, and the parents should have been at work. I have no doubt there were drug deals happening down there, late-night noise, and all sorts of antisocial behaviour — and even then, it wouldn’t have justified targeting her.
